---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
const title = "How to identify the Asian hornet (Vespa velutina)";
const description = "Identification guide to distinguish the Asian hornet from wasps, honey bees and the European hornet.";
---

<Base {title} {description}>
  <article class="card">
    <h1>How to identify the Asian hornet (<em>Vespa velutina</em>)</h1>
    <p>
      The Asian hornet is an invasive species established in France and now spreading into the UK.
      Quick, accurate identification is important to protect pollinators and prevent false reports.
    </p>

    <h2>Key features</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Dark brown/black body</li>
      <li>Broad orange band near the end of the abdomen</li>
      <li>Yellow legs (“yellow socks”)</li>
      <li>Black head with orange/yellow face</li>
      <li>Brown-tinted wings</li>
      <li>Smaller than the European hornet (<em>Vespa crabro</em>)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Nests</h2>
    <p>
      Large papery nests, up to 80 cm, usually smooth with a side entrance.
      Found high in trees but also in sheds or roof spaces. Never disturb a nest yourself.
    </p>

    <h2>Confusion species</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-2">
      <div>
        <img src="/images/asian-hornet.jpg" alt="Asian hornet" />
        <p><strong>Asian hornet</strong> – dark body, orange band, yellow legs.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src="/images/european-hornet.jpg" alt="European hornet" />
        <p><strong>European hornet</strong> – larger, more yellow, reddish thorax.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src="/images/common-wasp.jpg" alt="Common wasp" />
        <p><strong>Common wasp</strong> – much smaller, striped yellow/black, thin waist.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src="/images/honeybee.jpg" alt="Honey bee" />
        <p><strong>Honey bee</strong> – smaller, furry, golden-brown, carries pollen baskets.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Comparison table</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Species</th>
          <th>Size</th>
          <th>Colour features</th>
          <th>Key giveaway</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Asian hornet</td>
          <td>19–24 mm (queen up to 30 mm)</td>
          <td>Dark body, orange band, yellow legs</td>
          <td>“Yellow socks”</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>European hornet</td>
          <td>Up to 35 mm</td>
          <td>More yellow, reddish thorax</td>
          <td>Larger, native</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Common wasp</td>
          <td>10–15 mm</td>
          <td>Bright yellow/black stripes</td>
          <td>Much smaller</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Honey bee</td>
          <td>10–12 mm</td>
          <td>Brown/golden, hairy</td>
          <td>Fuzzy, pollen baskets</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Reporting a sighting</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>In France</strong>: report sightings through your regional authority or government portal.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>In the UK</strong>: use the 
        <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/asian-hornet-uk-sightings" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          Asian Hornet Watch app
        </a> or DEFRA’s online form.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Identification criteria adapted from UK Government and Non-Native Species Secretariat guidance (Open Government Licence v3.0).</em></p>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }
  th, td {
    border: 1px solid #2a3340;
    padding: 0.5rem;
    text-align: left;
  }
  th {
    background: #12161b;
  }
</style>

